You need to find a point on the line that is also on the line parallel to $\begin{pmatrix}2 \\ 1\end{pmatrix}$ and passing through the origin. So, the vector $\begin{pmatrix}a \\ b\end{pmatrix}$ should be proportional to $\begin{pmatrix}2 \\ 1\end{pmatrix}$ and lie on the line. The line can be written in the form
\begin{align*}
y = \frac{1}{4}x + 1.
\end{align*}
A vector parallel to $\begin{pmatrix}2 \\ 1\end{pmatrix}$ is of the form $\begin{pmatrix}2k \\ k\end{pmatrix}$ for some scalar $k$. We need to find the value of $k$ such that the vector $\begin{pmatrix}2k \\ k\end{pmatrix}$ lies on the line $y = \frac{1}{4}x + 1$. Substituting $x = 2k$ and $y = k$ into the equation of the line, we get
\begin{align*}
k &= \frac{1}{4}(2k) + 1\\
k &= \frac{1}{2}k + 1\\
\frac{1}{2}k &= 1\\
k &= 2.
\end{align*}
So the vector is $\begin{pmatrix}2 \cdot 2 \\ 2\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}4 \\ 2\end{pmatrix}$. </think>
